<TEXT>
the remains of gen omar torrijos a 
former panamanian military leader were stolen tuesday from the 
crypt of a roman catholic church in the capital a police chief 
said 
leslie loaiza director of the judicial police said relatives 
of torrijos told police they believed the ashes were stolen from 
the corazon de maria roman catholic church in the afternoon 
a witness gave police the description of two suspects believed 
to have made off with them loaiza said in a live interview on 
kwradio continente he refused to give details other than repeat 
we have their descriptions 
loaiza said the generals eldest son martin torrijos and 
martins brotherinlaw marcelino jaen filed a complaint with 
judicial authorities 
torrijos the subject of the graham greene book getting to 
know the general seized power in a coup oct 11 1968 and ruled 
panama as a military strongman until his death in a plane crash 
july 31 1979 
his body remained in a mausoleum erected in his honor at nearby 
fort amador where us and panamanian military forces had a joint 
command until late december when the panamanian defense forces 
were disbanded following the american military invasion to oust 
torrijos protege gen manuel antonio noriega 
torrijos had celebrated panamanian nationalism and was behind 
the panama canal treaties under which the canal will be turned 
over from the united states to panama by the year 2000 
however his nationalist ideas fell from favor following the 
invasion and return to a civilianled government 
on feb 17 his body was removed from the mausoleum by his 
family cremated and the ashes deposited in the church crypt 
his daughter raquel torrijos said at the time the decision was 
taken because relatives had received anonymous calls saying the 
generals tomb would be desecrated and his remains stolen 
</TEXT>
