<TEXT>
kay orr made history in 1986 when she 
became the nations first republican woman to be elected a 
governor but democrats eyeing her low job approval ratings hope 
her tenure itself soon will be history 
mrs orr whose troubles began in 1987 when she pushed through a 
tax overhaul that turned out to be a tax increase acknowledges she 
has problems but says they can be overcome 
we need to get across our message and our record of 
accomplishment she said in a recent interview were working 
on it 
four democrats in a field of seven are in a tooclosetocall 
race for their partys nomination in the may 15 primary 
mrs orr 51 faces only token primary opposition but 
nonetheless is running nononsense television commercials and has 
raised nearly 1 million in campaign contributions 
in one tv ad she acknowledges the political faux pas on the tax 
package and says i made a mistake 
the governor and her pollster dispute a recent omaha 
worldherald poll that put her job approval rating at 39 percent 
the lowest in the 20year history of the poll she said her own 
polling showed her with a 52 percent approval rating statewide 
state gop chairman norm riffel contends that mrs orrs 
political strength will prove ample once she has a single opponent 
to run against rather than seven democratic foes training their 
fire on her 
democrats seeking to unseat her include former omaha mayor mike 
boyle omaha attorneybusinessman ben nelson lincoln mayor bill 
harris and bill hoppner of lincoln a businessman and former top 
aide to sens bob kerrey and jim exon 
mrs orr appeared to be on an historic roll when she was elected 
in 1986 she defeated democrat helen boosalis in the nations first 
gubernatorial race in which both major party candidates were women 
another political first had come in 1982 when she was elected state 
treasurer and thus became the first woman elected to a statewide 
constitutional office 
an early and ardent supporter of former president reagan mrs 
orr was cochairman of the platform committee at the 1988 
republican national convention president bush and vice president 
dan quayle both have visited nebraska in recent months to campaign 
for her 
mrs orr came under fire when she pushed through a rewrite of 
the states income tax system in 1987 along with major legislation 
giving tax breaks to business for job creation and new investment 
critics said at the time it was a tax increase for lower and 
middleincome nebraskans mrs orr who had campaigned on a pledge 
to fight new or higher taxes first argued that it wouldnt be a 
tax increase period she later acknowledged that the tax burden of 
some would increase but the overall income tax rewrite would be 
revenue neutral she was wrong again 
mrs orr is hoping to turn the tax issue around and use it to 
her benefit now that the 1990 legislature has overridden her veto 
of a bill to raise state sales tax and income tax rates to help 
reduce property taxes 
she presents herself as having learned a lesson in 1987 and 
being thus dedicated to protecting taxpayers from a program she 
says wont guarantee property tax relief 
on the democratic side harris and hoppner have raised questions 
about nelsons connections direct or indirect with the junk bond 
industry nelson said his specialty was ensuring that companies 
complied with government regulations in that area 
to criticize me is like criticizing the fireman for the 
fire he said 
