communications problems with a circling us air 
force gunship may have hampered efforts by american commandos to 
seize a civilian airport at the start of the panama invasion 
janes defense weekly reports 
four navy seal commandos were killed and eight wounded in the 
first stages of the december invasion as they tried to secure the 
civil airfield at paitilla on the southeast coast of panama city 
janes reported that the sea air and land commandos could not 
communicate with the ac130 gunship which could have provided 
valuable intelligence and fire support 
excerpts of the article came in a magazine release monday ahead 
of the issues publication saturday 
it said the aircrafts sensors and night vision equipment might 
have been able to spot panamanian defense forces troops and alert 
the seals it said the seals could also have called upon the 
gunship for highly accurate targeted firepower to suppress the 
panamanian troops 
janes said in a report from washington that a force of 48 seals 
was ordered to secure the airport where panamas thenleader gen 
manuel antonio noriega kept his private plane 
american officials feared noriega who was wanted on drug 
charges in the united states would flee in the plane 
the magazine said the seals encountered snipers almost as soon 
as they landed at the airport it said they achieved gunfire 
superiority within five minutes and disabled noriegas aircraft 
by firing antitank rounds into it but still lost men 
the seal leadership is examining how the fatalities and 
casualties happened the magazine said 
it quoted an unidentified senior navy official close to 
operation just cause as saying the organization looked at 
whether the seals were adequately armed and whether the mission was 
appropriate for the relatively small number of seals deployed 
the magazine said the air force has told the navy it was able to 
communicate with all other units except the seals suggesting 
that the seals were the reason for the lack of communications 
it said the seals maintain they tried unsuccessfully to call the 
ac130 on every possible frequency and that the aircraft did not 
respond janes said that the next day the seals were able to 
communicate easily with other ac130s brought in to fly air cover 
it quoted the naval official as saying it was not known why 
communications with the gunship failed he was quoted as saying it 
was unclear whether there would have been fewer casualties had the 
seals been able to talk to the planes crew 
janes said the us navy and us special operations command 
have not provided public details of the gunfire exchange between 
the seals and the panamanian units 
