exxon corp assembled summer cleanup 
crews to return to the soiled shores of prince william sound today 
with no word on whether they may use chemicals that encourage 
oileating bacteria 
workers will stop short of using fertilizers until alaska and 
coast guard officials decide whether they should be allowed 
some state officials worry the chemicals in the fertilizers 
could be toxic alaska can veto their use but authority for the 
rest of exxons cleanup lies with coast guard rear adm david e 
ciancaglini who has approved parts of the plan 
state officials hoped to decide today or wednesday on the 
fertilizers used in a cleanup method called bioremediation said 
mike hilley of the alaska department of environmental conservation 
the cleanup from exxons march 1989 spill of nearly 11 million 
gallons of north slope crude was suspended last september and 
officials monitored conditions through winter 
the spill was the nations largest and coated hundreds of miles 
of shoreline killing hundreds of otters and thousands of birds and 
other animals 
exxon proposed sending eight mobile crews to clean shoreline 
still soiled from the spill three of the vessels already are at 
work in the sound and the gulf of alaska exxon spokesman fred 
davis said two more ships were to be launched today and the rest 
later in the week 
exxon plans to employ about 1100 people for the summer cleanup 
effort about onetenth the number it used last summer 
while the bioremediation debate continues crews today were to 
begin manual pickup and raking at the most environmentally 
sensitive shorelines ciancaglini said 
top priority will be sites considered important for commercial 
fishing and and recreation officials said 
ciancaglini has approved less controversial portions of the oil 
companys cleanup plan and said he hoped to make a final ruling on 
the rest by may 9 
exxon has said its studies of 574 miles of shoreline so far 
showed twothirds without any oil at all 22 percent with very 
light oiling and 13 percent with a narrow to wide band of 
weathered crude along sections 
the alaska department of environmental conservation said 79 
percent of the shoreline sites affected by the spill still had oil 
