<TEXT>
the bush administration will consider 
returning iraq to its list of countries that sponsor international 
terrorism secretary of state james a baker iii told congress 
today 
baker said iraqs efforts to develop a nuclear program was 
particularly disturbing iraq was removed from the list in 1984 
i think we have to take a look at this issue and we will be 
taking a look at this issue baker told a senate appropriations 
subcommittee a day after the state departments annual report to 
congress on terrorism 
that report cited six nations for sponsoring international 
terrorism including syria and iran which won praise from 
president bush on monday for their help in the release of american 
hostage frank h reed in lebanon 
countries on the list are denied advanced american technology 
and us support for various international bank loans in addition 
to syria and iran the list includes libya cuba north korea and 
south yeman 
sen robert kasten rwis told baker that whatever the 
administrations decision he would promote legislation in congress 
to put iraq on the terrorism list 
baker said the administration was considering several sanctions 
against the iraqi government including a denial of credits for 
agricultural purchases but he cautioned we ought to be at least 
conscious if we take that action our allies will be very quick to 
pick up our market there he said 
the state department terrorism report credited syria and libya 
with showing some improvement and it said iran had a slight 
decline from 32 incidents of supporting terrorism in 1988 to 28 
last year 
the report released monday recorded a sharp drop worldwide as 
well as among american victims sixteen us citizens were killed 
and 19 wounded compared with 192 killed and 40 wounded in 1988 
the bombing of pan american flight 103 over lockerbie scotland 
accounted for most of the 1988 deaths 
overall the number of terrorist incidents fell off nearly 38 
percent from 856 in 1988 to 528 last year 
syria and iran remain on the state departments list of 
supporters of terrorism though syrias willingness to help 
liberate western hostages and a pledge by president hafez assad to 
punish perpetrators were noted 
on the other hand syria continued to provide support and safe 
haven for a wide variety of groups engaged in terrorism the report 
said among them is the militant hezbollah group with which 
holders of the six remaining american hostages in lebanon are 
considered linked 
iran meanwhile was accused in the report of continuing to use 
terrorism after the death of the ayatollah ruhollah khomeini in 
june in pursuit of its foreign policy goals 
examples cited by the report included a call for the death of 
salman rushdie author of the satanic verses and increased 
attacks against interests of saudi arabia including explosion of 
two bombs during the islamic pilgrimage to mecca 
president hashemi rafsanjani sometimes credited with taking a 
moderate stance was criticized for exhorting palestinians to kill 
americans and other westerners in order to avenge palestinians 
killed during the rebellion against israel on the west bank and in 
gaza 
rafsanjani also publicly encouraged the hijacking of airplanes 
and the blowing up of factories the report said 
libya while listed as a sponsor of terrorism was credited in 
the report with continuing to show public signs of moderation 
there were no incidents throughout the year directly attributable 
to the north african country led by col moammar gadhafi the 
report said 
with the level of terrorism in sharp decline worldwide the only 
spectacular operation was the bombing of a french airliner over 
niger last september causing 171 deaths 
also the afghan government curtailed its terrorist campaign in 
neighboring pakistan and operations by groups associated with the 
palestine liberation organization sharply declined after chairman 
yasser arafat publicly renounced terrorism in december 1988 the 
report said 
a change in accounting by the state departments 
counterterrorism office also contributed to the dropoff for the 
first time violence by palestinians against palestinians on the 
west bank and in gaza is not considered an act of international 
terrorism 
the reason the report said in a footnote is that the attacks 
are a form of intraethnic violence meaning within the same 
group this helped bring the overall total down 
the 528 incidents of terrorism recorded by the state department 
resulted in 390 victims killed and 397 wounded fourteen terrorists 
were killed and 23 wounded 
in 1988 by contrast 638 victims were killed and 1125 were 
wounded 
most of the attacks occurred in the middle east followed by 
latin america and western europe 
