<DOCNO> AP900501-0086 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the federal aviation administration and 
airline industry joined forces tuesday to oppose legislation that 
would increase the federal role in inspecting aging airliners 
anthony broderick faa associate administrator told a house 
hearing that the bill would increase government liability and could 
cost between 1 million and 2 million per aircraft 
it would take five years to hire and train the needed 
inspectors he said 
faa inspectors oversee regular checks and maintenance conducted 
by the airlines but dont routinely dismantle and inspect airliners 
themselves 
the hearing of the house public works aviation subcommittee came 
two years and two days after an 18foot section of the roof ripped 
off an aging aloha airlines boeing 737 in flight over hawaii 
sweeping a flight attendant to her death that incident prompted 
new concern about aging airliners and led to a governmentindustry 
task force that planned faa response to the problem 
the average us airliner is nearly 13 years old and more than 
onefourth of the planes are more than 20 years old thats 
expected to increase as growing demand keeps aircraft from being 
retired 
the bill proposed by democratic and republican leaders of the 
aviation subcommittee would require the faa to thoroughly inspect 
each airliner during the last year of its economic design life 
which could vary with each aircraft according to how it is used 
unless approved in an faa inspection planes would be grounded 
after they reach the predetermined design life 
the bill would fundamentally change the way faa works to ensure 
aviation safety replacing airline inspections with faa 
inspections broderick told the panel 
this proposed departure from traditional practices troubles us 
quite a bit he said 
he said the faa workload in the first year would be something 
almost impossible to contemplate conducting as we would be 
required to inspect over 1000 aircraft a task that is simply 
unrealistic 
broderick said the faa is already having a difficult time coping 
with its inspection duties because of rapid growth of the industry 
since the aloha accident the faa has changed its approach to 
airline aging from one of requiring frequent inspections to 
mandating changes of critical parts of aircraft when they reach a 
set number of cycles or takeoffs and landings 
i feel strongly that the agencys aging aircraft program 
represents the best thinking and cooperative efforts of government 
and industry broderick said 
robert e doll united airlines vice president who heads the 
governmentindustry task force said adding inspection duties for 
the faa could impinge other safety efforts of both the airlines and 
the government 
he said the possibility of increased liability for the 
government could bring extensive disassembly and exhaustive 
inspections of planes that would lead to repair costs so great as 
to provoke the premature retirement of airworthy airplanes 
that doll said could lead to a shortage of aircraft as the 
demand for air travel grows 
he said it would also be very difficult to determine the design 
life of each aircraft because some parts are sensitive to flight 
hours others to flight cycles and still others to calendar age 
doll proposed however that the faa increase its attention to 
new air carriers to ensure that they have adequate inspection and 
maintenance programs 
</TEXT>
