up to 700 vietnamese children and young people 
living in southeast asian refugee camps will be granted political 
asylum in this country immigration and naturalization service 
commissioner gene mcnary announced tuesday 
the young people described by immigration authorities as 
unaccompanied by parents or adult relatives were all under age 18 
when they arrived at refugee camps some are now in their early 20s 
the ins will begin interviewing the applicants this month to 
screen them for political asylum mcnary said the first refugees 
from the group are expected to arrive in the united states in july 
and the rest by years end mcnary said in a statement 
immigration authorities said the young people were unable to 
qualify as political refugees when previously interviewed because 
they were too young or inarticulate at the time to provide evidence 
of political persecution 
many of these young people and children have families still 
living in vietnam including fathers who fought in the south 
vietnamese army during the vietnam war which ended 15 years ago 
their lives are in suspension and it seemed like an 
appropriate time to go back and reinterview those people in the 
most generous manner said ralph thomas deputy assistant ins 
commissioner for refugee asylum and parole 
we anticipate that the large bulk of them will be admitted as 
refugees thomas said 
most of the children and young people are living in refugee 
camps in thailand others are in the philippines indonesia and 
hong kong 
since the war ended more than 1 million vietnamese refugees 
have been admitted to the united states 
some of the 700 young people have relatives living in this 
country authorities said 
mcnary said he hopes the initiative will set an example for 
other nations to implement the comprehensive plan of action an 
international agreement for resettling indochinese refugees 
