tens of thousands of workers and 
students staged demonstrations throughout south korea on tuesday to 
protest police raids that crushed strikes at a state broadcast 
network and the nations largest shipyard 
violent street protests broke out in seoul and at least 17 
provincial cities on the may day labor holiday students and 
workers at auto plants subways shipyards and broadcast stations 
held rallies or clashed with riot police hurling rocks and 
firebombs 
more than 80000 people took part in tuesdays protests the 
largest this year news reports said 
police reported arrests and injuries but gave no overall 
figures in seoul alone about 150 people were arrested bringing 
to nearly 500 the number detained in the capital in the past four 
days reports said 
across the nation in that same period authorities said 80 
policemen and 14 workers were injured and nine workers formally 
charged with instigating labor unrest 
crush president roh taewoo who suppresses labor yelled 
hundreds of radical students hurling firebombs and rocks at riot 
police outside seouls yonsei university 
the government said it perceived the current labor unrest as a 
crisis 
we cannot help taking strong measures against the labor 
protests which have political overtones prime minister kang 
younghoon said tuesday after a meeting with aides and leaders of 
the governing democratic liberal party 
kang and other officials expressed concern that the already 
slumping korean economy might suffer further unless the unrest 
eases a prolonged labor dispute in 1987 slowed exports and led to 
increased unemployment 
korean exports shrank 14 percent in the first quarter this year 
and share prices on the korean stock market took the biggest 
singleday plunge ever on monday hitting an 18month low 
wages are not a main issue in the current protests workers are 
demanding the release of jailed union leaders and more freedom to 
organize labor without government interference 
major protests were reported in the southeastern industrial city 
of ulsan where police stormed the hyundai heavy industries co 
shipyard the nations largest over the weekend to end a threeday 
strike 
the police action touched off four days of violent sympathy 
protests by workers in ulsan and other industrial regions 
on tuesday about 4000 workers in ulsan hurling rocks and 
firebombs fought police near the shipyard as an estimated 40000 
workers held rallies elsewhere in the city reports said 
a 41yearold worker in ulsan was seriously injured when he 
leaped from the second floor of a house while being chased by 
police 
at the shipyard about 50 militant workers were holding out atop 
a 240foot crane for the fourth day tuesday the workers fled there 
when police raided the stikebound shipyard last saturday 
at the nearby hyundai motor co the nations largest car maker 
about 20000 workers decided to extend until sunday a sympathy 
strike that began monday and initially was scheduled for two days 
the shipyard and the car plant are the main arms of the giant 
hyundai group one of the largest conglomerates in south korea 
which reported 48 billion in 1989 sales 
