<TEXT>
education programs to discourage federal 
inmates from resuming drug habits after their release are being set 
up at eight federal prisons the justice department said tuesday 
as many as 975 inmates at eight federal prison facilities will 
participate in the two programs that will also provide postrelease 
supervision said michael quinlan director of the bureau of 
prisons 
the only effective drug treatment is treatment that is offered 
toward the end of the sentence and is tied into the community 
integration process quinlan told reporters 
the approach is being taken because prison officials decided 
we have a unique captive audience and we ought to take advantage 
of it quinlan said 
additionally all new federal prison inmates who have a history 
of drug abuse will be required to complete a drug education 
program quinlan said 
new inmates who refuse to participate in this program will be 
denied privileges extended to other prisoners and will be eligible 
for only the lowestpaying jobs in work programs quinlan said 
the number of federal inmates with a history of drug use has 
grown dramatically in the last decade quinlan said currently 45 
percent of the 56200 federal inmates had drug abuse problems when 
they were sentenced to prison he said 
in all the bureau of prisons expects to spend 6 million on 
drugprevention programs during the current fiscal year up from 
225 million last year quinlan said 
the new programs were announced at a press briefing a day before 
the senate labor and human resources committee was scheduled to 
question justice department officials about a cutoff of 5 million 
in drugtreatment funds to state and local prison systems 
the money which was available last year in grants to state and 
local officials was shifted to other programs during the current 
fiscal year 
clifford j white iii deputy assistant attorney general in the 
office of justice programs and gerald regier acting director of 
the bureau fo justice assistance were scheduled to be questioned 
on wednesday 
the new programs for federal prison inmates completing their 
sentences are based on the notion that a person is addicted to 
drugs regardless of whether the sentence may interrupt the ability 
to get that substance quinlan said 
if people do not learn to deal with that addiction they are 
going to return to the same life style quinlan said 
intensive 1000hour drugeducation programs have already been 
set up at federal facilities in butner nc and lexington ky an 
identical program is also planned for the federal prison in 
tallahassee fla quinlan said 
a total of 350 inmates in the last 15 to 24 months of their 
sentences will participate in the programs he said 
in september 500hour education programs will be offfered at 
prisons in sheridan ore seagoville texas rochester minn 
oxford wis and fairton nj 
the programs at each of those facilities will serve 100 to 125 
inmates each year with counseling and individual therapy 
