<TEXT>
a 4yearold boy is facing a tricky 
procedure of using umbilical cord blood from the birth of his 
sister on tuesday to help treat his rare form of leukemia doctors 
said 
michael sancilios form of leukemia afflicts less than 1 percent 
of childhood leukemia victims children with this disease 
generally survive less than a year after diagnosis said stephen 
rodgers the familys pediatrician michael was diagnosed with 
chronic myelogenous leukemia in midmarch 
normal treatment is a bone marrow transplant rodgers said but 
the chance of quickly finding a bone marrow match from a donor is 
statistically slim with so little time doctors are gambling on 
the umbilical blood transfusion 
thats where christina grace sancilio comes in she was born by 
caesarian section tuesday morning at virginia beach general 
hospital dr leslie l wasserman who delivered both christina and 
michael said the newborn is healthy and doing well 
using a syringe wasserman made two collections of umbilical 
blood one with the placenta still attached the other with the 
placenta delivered the one cup of blood is en route to indiana 
university scientists who will check to see if christinas blood 
matches michaels 
wasserman said the procedure was difficult because the surgery 
team had to ensure that none of the mothers blood contaminated the 
umbilical cord blood wasserman said a caesarian section was 
performed because of 33yearold denise sancilios difficulties in 
delivering michael 
physicians put the chances for a match at 1in4 far better 
than the 1in20000 chance of a match in the general population 
rodgers said this was the first time the experimental procedure 
would be tried for a leukemia patient 
umbilical blood contains special cells called stem cells which 
develop bone marrow in babies in their first nine months rodgers 
said christina already has the necessary stem cells to develop bone 
marrow 
if the blood matches michaels the cells will be grown in a 
laboratory at the university which pioneered the procedure for the 
treatment of some forms of anemia once scientists have grown the 
cells they will be transfused into michael after all his diseased 
bone marrow has been killed by radiation 
the cells are injected into the patients heart and act as if 
they were in a newborn heading straight for the bone to produce 
bone marrow 
we dont know what all the problems might be at this point 
said rodgers its all going to take several months and michael 
will be close to the end of his disease when we try the 
transfusion 
even if the procedure is successful rodgers said the child 
faces a lifetime of treatment to ensure the body does not reject 
the new bone marrow 
