<TEXT>
defense secretary dick cheney raised the ante 
in the pentagon budget battle tuesday by extending a worldwide 
freeze on military construction and ordering 207 projects 
including navy ports in texas alabama mississippi and new york 
be reviewed for possible cancellation 
theres serious doubt about whether or not we will get the 
levels of funding from congress that will allow us to go forward 
with these programs cheney said 
the move is expected to fuel the debate between those in 
congress who want to squeeze pentagon spending and lawmakers who 
want to protect local jobs 
cheney said the freeze order which he imposed in january and 
now will last until june 15 affects more than 7 billion in new 
contracts the 207 construction projects to be reviewed are valued 
at 12 billion he said 
at a news conference cheney accused some members of congress of 
a certain amount of hypocrisy because they publicly advocate 
smaller pentagon budgets even as they lobby him in private to 
protect homestate military programs 
some of these actions may not be popular with members of 
congress who want to cut the defense budget even as they plead to 
save the projects in their own states and districts cheney said 
but when tight budgets force dedicated soldiers to turn in 
their uniforms and leave the service i cannot put construction 
projects ahead of people 
the 207 sites under study include strategic home ports in 
ingleside texas mobile ala pascagoula miss and staten 
island ny 
the majority of the projects under review are overseas many in 
west germany planned improvements or construction of hangars 
maintenance facilities family housing projects schools for 
military dependents and medical units are among the items targeted 
but several of the domestic sites targeted for study carry 
bigmoney pricetags 
the statement said that besides the four ports the review will 
also include a 110 million project at a rocket test facility at 
arnold tenn 60 million in improvements at fort hood and red 
river army depot in texas and a 37 million project at a 
consolidated maintenance facility at tooele utah 
rep patricia schroeder dcolo chairwoman of the house armed 
services subcommittee on military installations and facilities 
said she was pleased with cheneys announcement because he targeted 
overseas work she has opposed 
in recent weeks cheney has taken steps to pare the defense 
budget including cutting from 132 to 75 the number of b2 stealth 
bombers it proposes buying and sharply reducing other warplane 
programs 
citing changes in the world situation and increasing budget 
limitations cheney said significant opportunities exist to 
reduce the cost and size of the dods infrastructure 
cheneys order directs that no new construction contracts be 
awarded for projects financed under the military construction 
budget approved by congress 
the 207 construction projects will be candidates for 
rescission which means cheney may recommend that congress revoke 
the funding approved for earlier projects 
a dod statement said deputy defense secretary donald atwood will 
review construction plans for possible cancellation and submit a 
proposed list of rescissions to cheney by june 1 
cheney said that if those lawmakers who are advocating slashing 
20 billion from president bushs 3069 billion request for budget 
authority get their way more than 207 projects would have to be 
canceled 
cheney said he took the action because the freeze ran out monday 
night not because the house had scheduled a vote on a budget 
committee proposal to reduce bushs defense budget request 
on capitol hill schroeder and rep charles bennett dfla 
introduced legislation that would close the home port on staten 
island and freeze funds for construction at five other home ports 
in everett wash ingleside texas pascagoula miss mobile 
ala and pensacola fla 
the ports in everett and pensacola werent included in cheneys 
review because they are nearly completed pentagon officials said 
the gao in testimony last month before the house armed services 
subcommittee on seapower and strategic and critical materials that 
bennett chairs recommended freezing spending on new home ports 
until the navy decides what it needs 
at the hearing new york mayor david dinkins said his city does 
not want the home port and cannot afford it eleven of the 
14member new york city congressional delegation and 16 members of 
the new york city council also opposed the project 
