<TEXT>
the bush administration backed a measure 
tuesday that would triple civil fines for employers who violate 
workplace safety laws but gave only limited support to legislation 
that creates new criminal offenses 
if enacted the higher civil penalties for occupational safety 
and health administration violations would be the first increase in 
osha fines in the agencys 20year history 
labor secretary elizabeth doles call for higher fines was 
viewed by organized labor supporters as a sign shes committed to 
worker safety and that the bush administration is improving osha 
organized labor considered the agency neglected under the reagan 
administration 
it was the first time osha has taken a stand on increased 
penalties 
at a senate hearing on proposed osha changes sen howard 
metzenbaum dohio urged assistant labor secretary gerard scannell 
to reconsider the agencys opposition to his plan that creates new 
felonies for willful violations that result in serious bodily 
injury or recklessly endanger human life 
metzenbaums plan also increases from six months to 10 years the 
jail term for willful violations that result in a workers death 
metzenbaum chairman of the senate labor subcommittee called 
the current sixmonth jail term an absurdly low penalty that 
sends a message to potential violators 
it says do not worry treat worker deaths and injuries as 
just another cost of doing business metzenbaum said 
osha supports changing the crime for a violation that results in 
a death from a misdemeanor to a felony but agency officials 
believe sentencing should be left to the courts scannell said 
in addition osha objects to the two new felonies metzenbaums 
measure creates because civil penalties which often result in 
employers quickly correcting workplace hazards are easier to 
settle than criminal penalties scannell said 
the creation of two new felonies he said would damage the 
departments ability to get businesses to quickly correct those 
hazards because more employers would appeal 
expansion of the criminal provisions will come at a very high 
price not only the price of diminished civil enforcement but even 
more tragic the higher price of delayed elimination of the 
hazards scannell said 
osha also announced support for helping state and local 
prosecutors in enforcing state criminal statues in relation to 
workplace injury or deaths 
scannell said osha supports a threefold increase in civil 
penalties to bring them in line with inflation 
under a plan by sen frank lautenberg dnj the 10000 fine 
for knowingly violating osha laws would increase to 30000 while a 
lesser violation set at 1000 would increase to 3000 
business groups testified against the measures to strengthen 
osha laws saying they were vague and would harm innocent 
businessmen 
decent and respectable employers will have greater exposure to 
criminal penalties than bank robbers drug dealers and common 
criminals said kirk fordice president of the associated general 
contractors of america 
fordice complained that the legislation did not address drug use 
by employees or acknowledge the need for workers to be 
accountable for meeting minimum standards of responsibility 
an estimated 10000 workers are killed each year on the job and 
about 70000 others are permanently disabled by workplace 
accidents according to aflcio figures 
