the bush administration wants to forgive some 
of the 117 billion owed by more than 70 countries for us food 
aid officials told congress tuesday 
it has still to decide how much would be forgiven and which 
countries would benefit 
william c ramsay deputy assistant secretary of state for 
energy resources and food policy said they would be the poorest 
countries if they have promised the world bank or the 
international monetary fund to undertake new policies 
the last requirement would exclude egypt for example which 
owes the most 26 billion egypt has been negotiating with the 
fund for years but has so far found its terms too difficult 
south korea which still owes over 600 million is too well off 
for debt forgiveness according to an official of the us agency 
for international development 
most of the beneficiaries would be african countries to which 
bush has already promised forgiveness of 1 billion worth of other 
debt ramsay said poor countries outside africa such as bangladesh 
and haiti may also win forgiveness of the food debt 
bangladesh owes over 1 billion for food aid as do indonesia 
and pakistan 
ramsay also asked for authority to make more grants of food aid 
instead of loans on generous terms many countries in urgent need 
of food aid have such large debt service burdens and weak economies 
that they can no longer afford even these generous terms he said 
ramsay testified before the subcommittee on international 
economic policy of the house foreign affairs committee which is 
considering bills that would allow the debt forgiveness envisioned 
by ramsay 
