the government tuesday offered to meet 
opposition parties threatening to boycott romanias first free 
elctions in more than 50 years 
the move follows the accusation by five major opposition parties 
that the national salvation front which dominates the provisional 
governing coalition is monopolizing power the opposition parties 
on monday threatened to boycott the may 20 elections 
the government offer also comes as a roundtheclock 
antigovernment protest in bucharest entered its 10th day 
the goverment said claims that the national salvation front was 
harassing opposition activists and using facilities left by the 
deposed communist party can be discussed with representatives of 
the government to eliminate any kind of suspicions and to 
improve some organizational aspects of the elections 
the statement said the goverment would guarantee the equality 
of chances from a technical point of view for all parties 
contesting the election 
the five opposition parties that are threatening to boycott the 
elections are the national peasants party the national liberal 
party the social democrat party the free democrat party and the 
socialist liberal party 
there was no immediate response from the parties to the 
goverment statement 
in bucharest 8000 protesters gathered in downtown university 
square to protest against the government of interim president ion 
iliescu which they claim favors preserving communism iliescu is a 
former communist official who became a critic of ceausescus in 
recent years 
organizers of the anticommunist protest said they have 
collected 4 million signatures for a petition to exclude all former 
communists from politics and government there was no way to 
independently verify their claim 
the national salvation front began ruling as an interim 
government shortly after the december revolution that deposed 
communist dictator nicolae ceausescu it then brought in opposition 
figures to form a coalition government but remained the dominant 
force 
on tuesday the crowed stood singing and chanting under a giant 
banner that read iliescu go back to where you came from 
