<TEXT>
the purchasers in the biggest savings and loan 
bailout of 1988 are enjoying millions of dollars of riskfree 
profits and regulators should renegotiate the deal sen howard 
metzenbaum said tuesday 
the ohio democrat said a federal home loan bank of dallas memo 
obtained by his senate judiciary subcommittee on antitrust shows 
taxpayers likely would have been better off if regulators 
liquidated first gibraltar bank of houston rather than bailing it 
out in december 1988 
the federal home loan bank board then the chief regulator of 
thrift institutions estimated it would have cost 5 billion to 
shut down the five bankrupt thrifts that were combined to form 
first gibraltar 
however a memo prepared in february 1989 by analyst jeff potter 
in dallas said the liquidation cost was grossly overstated by 
about 16 billion metzenbaum said indicating the sale may have 
been unnecessary 
instead of liquidating the bank board pledged 5 billion in 
future aid and 12 billion in tax benefits to new york financier 
and revlon chairman ronald o perelman and other investors who put 
up 315 million 
including the tax benefits first gibraltar now the largest 
thrift in texas and among the 20 largest in the nation enjoyed the 
best return on investment of any thrift in the nation last year 
according to metzenbaums aides 
it received 461 million in federal assistance in 1989 enabling 
it to post a profit of 129 million the senator said 
these overly generous payments are government guarantees that 
give little incentive to manage the assets of the sampl profitably 
they also suggest that the government drove a very poor bargain 
for taxpayers metzenbaum said in a letter to l william seidman 
chairman of the resolution trust corp which has assumed 
responsibility for reviewing the 1988 bailouts 
metzenbaum said the findings of his staff which reviewed 35000 
documents related to the 1988 deals dramatically underscore 
the need to renegotiate the first gibraltar sale and other 
transactions 
our investigation has found evidence that bidding on several 
deals was irregular and done in haste billions in federal 
subsidies and thrift assets were juggled in a rush to close as many 
deals as possible before the end of 1988 he wrote 
first gibraltar chairman gerald j ford defended his 
institutions deal with the government saying it was concluded 
after a vigorous and highly competitive auction 
he said his sampl has restored stability and depositor confidence 
to the texas thrift industry through a forwardlooking program of 
assets management branch consolidation and operating 
efficiencies 
federal regulators at the time of the 1988 deals defended the 
transactions as the best they could do because they lacked the 
cash to pay off depositors they were forced to keep insolvent 
institutions afloat by pledging future assistance they said 
