a federal judge said tuesday he would allow 
sworn videotaped statements from two key defense witnesses in the 
philippines to be introduced at imelda marcos fraud trial 
mrs marcos attorneys say one of the witnesses orlando dulay 
will testify that he was present when ferdinand marcos recovered a 
hoard of gold known as the yamashita treasure and that he helped 
transport the gold to marcos home 
the yamashita treasure was a huge cache of gold supposed to have 
been hidden in the philippines by gen tomoyuki yamashita the 
japanese military commander stationed there in the closing days of 
world war ii 
marcos who died in exile in hawaii last september claimed that 
the gold was the primary source of his wealth no evidence of the 
gold has ever been found 
proof of this serendipitous discovery would be offered to 
refute the governments contention that marcos amassed his wealth 
through systematic plundering of the philippine treasury us 
district judge john f keenan said in a written ruling 
the judge also approved the taking of a deposition from fransico 
tantuico who was in charge of the philippine audit organization 
between 1976 and 1986 tantuico will testify that reports prepared 
by his department disprove allegations of corruption by the 
marcoses 
mrs marcos 60 is accused of helping her late husband loot the 
philippine treasury of more than 220 million to buy new york 
properties and support lavish living 
her codefendant saudi financier adnan khashoggi is charged 
with helping the marcoses conceal their ownership of four new york 
buildings and artworks purchased with the allegedly stolen funds 
keenan said lawyers for mrs marcos can interview the witnesses 
in the philippines during the second week of june when the trial 
will be in recess the videotaped statements will then be shown to 
jurors 
the judge denied a motion to allow mrs marcos to go to the 
philippines with her attorneys he also ruled against allowing her 
lawyers to interview president corazon aquino who ousted marcos 
and numerous other potential defense witnesses 
keenan said defense claims that the us and philippine 
governments were hectoring and intimidating potential defense 
witnesses in the philippines appear exaggerated 
the aquino government has refused to let mrs marcos return 
since she and her husband left the country after marcos defeat as 
president in february 1986 
testimony tuesday focused on the alleged embezzlement of funds 
in the philippines 
one witness said the chief of the agency that handled japanese 
war reparations to the philippines took commissions that were 
deposited into swiss bank accounts held by marcos 
andres genito a former employee of two japanese trading 
companies said he made the payments to gen eugenio balao a close 
marcos associate who was in charge of the war reparations 
commission from 1966 until it expired in the mid 1970s 
i jokingly told him general balao that this is a large sum 
of money is it for you he said are you kidding this goes to 
president marcos said genito who now owns a liquor store in 
los angeles 
the witness testified that he accompanied balao on numerous 
occasions to hong kong where the general converted the commissions 
from japanese yen to us dollars genito said balao told him he 
deposited the money into swiss accounts held by marcos 
genito said he made the payments during all the years balao 
served on the reparations commission but he did not say how much 
money was involved 
