a federal judge tuesday night halted the 
scheduled execution of twotime killer bobby lewis shaw a few 
hours after the u s supreme court declined to intervene in the 
case 
shaw had been scheduled to die by injection at 1201 am 
wednesday at potosi correctional center 
however us district judge edward l filippine issued a stay 
at the request of shaws lawyer don wolff the judge said wolffs 
petition contained 12 grounds for relief and that he needed time to 
review the issues 
given the unique circumstances surrounding the filing of this 
petition the nature of the issues raised and the volume of the 
material that must be reviewed a stay of execution is necessary 
he said 
the nations highest court earlier voted 54 against stopping 
the execution 
on tuesday afternoon the missouri coalition against the death 
penalty asked gov john ashcroft to give shaw a reprieve because 
the prisoner does not comprehend the charges against him said 
the groups spokeswoman martha schieber 
its in the interest of the common good that no death penalty 
be imposed on a person that suffers from a mental disease or 
defect ms schieber said there is evidence that mr shaw 
suffers from a mental disease or defect 
ashcrofts spokesman bob ferguson said his boss referred the 
application for a reprieve to the state parole board ashcroft 
supports capital punishment and has not previously stopped an 
execution 
wolff said a psychiatrist and a psychologist who examined shaw 
at the potosi correctional center on monday agreed that the 
38yearold st louis man suffers from mental disease or 
defect they found shaw suffers from dementia memory loss and 
doesnt understand the penalty he faces or the arguments in his 
case the attorney said 
wolff had prepared briefs for state and federal courts 
incorporating the psychological findings and other arguments 
i am so busy i havent had time to be optimistic or 
pessimistic wolff said 
