<TEXT>
prelude to a kiss the bewitching fantasy by 
craig lucas has made the journey from offbroadway to broadway 
with most of the magic intact 
the big question for the play which opened tuesday at the helen 
hayes theater was what would happen to it once leading man alec 
baldwin left to do a movie and was replaced by timothy hutton 
well the verdict is not yet in on hutton he undoubtedly will 
get better in the role but right now the actor is giving a tense 
and tentative performance concentrating more on his lines than on 
his character once hutton relaxes he should do fine he has a 
boyish bewilderment that seems exactly right considering the odd 
but sweet plot 
the play itself is just as charming as ever and the rest of the 
original cast is even more accomplished than when prelude to a 
kiss first opened in march at offbroadways circle rep 
the story is a modern new york romance boymeetsgirl 
boylosesgirl and then boyfindsgirl in the strangest of 
circumstances it starts as a romantic comedy with peter played by 
hutton meeting rita marylouise parker at a party they fall in 
love visit her parents in new jersey and then get married 
the play builds to the wedding scene where the bride is kissed 
by a mysterious old man played by barnard hughes suddenly they 
have exchanged souls much of the evenings pleasure comes from the 
realization that hughes in a funny touching performance is now 
the young woman and parker the elderly gent and lucas dialogue 
is unerring perfectly capturing the cosmic transfer of these two 
very different personalities 
but there is a darkness around the edges of this fairy tale 
lucas also deals with the transitory nature of life and love 
especially as peter begins to realize the girl he has married is 
not the woman he thought she was it makes him wonder just what 
love is merely a physical attraction or something more 
parker is especially endearing particularly in the early scenes 
when she displays a goofy offcenter sense of comedy larry 
bryggman and debra monk excel as her understandably worried 
parents and there is an expert comic cameo by john dossett as the 
young mans sardonic best friend 
director norman rene a longtime lucas collaborator handles 
the play with a light playful touch that never turns preachy even 
in its more serious moments prelude to a kiss celebrates the 
unexpected nature of romance its that sense of adventure that 
makes the play such a delight 
