<TEXT>
the general assembly on tuesday adopted a 
declaration calling on industrialized nations to devote 07 percent 
of their gross national product to the development of third world 
nations 
the 106nation assembly adopted the declaration by concensus to 
avoid an open split between western and developing nations 
the united states opposes the idea of setting targets for the 
amount of aid contributed and it is was unclear whether many 
industrialized nations would abide by the nonbinding declaration 
the declaration is expected to provide general guidelines to 
helping underdeveloped nations 
i am grateful for the spirit of harmony and compromise which 
made it possible to reach agreement assembly president joseph 
garba of nigeria said in a statement 
bolivian ambassador hugo navajasmogro speaking for developing 
nations called the declaration and session landmarks in a new 
chapter in the economic history of the united nations 
this is a message of hope and opportunity for the poorest 
sectors of the world the developing countries for twothirds of 
mankind 
us envoy edward marks senior adviser to the economic session 
told the assembly this declaration represents an important new 
step in the way we all look at economic development 
but he also said the united states opposes the idea of aid 
targets believing that each state should be responsible for their 
own development 
the international economic environment while important plays 
a supporting role marks said 
one us diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity said 
