<TEXT>
andy gustafson wears two wedding rings 
one from his new marriage one from the marriage that ended in 
murder 
two and a half years ago gustafson 36 a smalltown lawyer 
returned home and found his wife raped and shot to death and his 
two children drowned in separate bathtubs 
a 17yearold neighborhood youth was arrested two days later and 
eventually sentenced to life in prison without parole for the 
murders the teen had apparently been in the house when mrs 
gustafson and her son returned home the daughter was killed when 
she came home later 
i was too afraid of going to look for my children because i 
was afraid id find them dead gustafson said of that day it 
was so shocking and unbelievable i screamed i wailed 
except for his moving eulogy at his familys funeral and his 
oneday testimony at the murder trial gustafson has remained out 
of the public eye 
he has not remained a victim 
on jan 1 1989 a date chosen to signify a new beginning 
gustafson remarried he has known his second wife carol 42 since 
they were married to others and both couples attended the townsend 
congregational church her husband died of a brain tumor in 1984 
after 15 years of marriage 
it certainly would have been much more difficult without 
her he said sitting in his booklined study i dont know 
whether i would have made it or not without her now i have a 
reason to get up in the morning something to live for 
rather than erase the past they make a point to remember both 
wear two wedding bands their new ones on their left ring fingers 
and the others from their first marriages on their right hands 
at their wedding carols first husbands father gave her away 
andys dead wifes brother sang carols matron of honor was her 
former sisterinlaw they had two ministers with ties to both of 
their first spouses 
your life is about your relationships when you lose them you 
lose your life in a way andy said you either get stuck or you 
go on and make a new life 
they both considered whether they were getting married too soon 
there were a few people in this town that were just aghast 
said carol a warm petite brunette but when youve gone through 
this kind of loss youre just glad the sun is shining every day 
life becomes more precious to you we didnt want to waste it 
the couple live in carols 10room yellow clapboard colonial on 
the townsend common the center of a picturebook new england town 
about 45 miles northwest of boston near the new hampshire state 
line 
the house is three doors from the church where the funeral was 
held for the gustafson family and where he married carol and just 
a few hundred yards from hillside cemetery where his family is 
buried 
andy has resumed his law practice just across the common 
starting over has not been easy 
his life was shattered in the late afternoon of dec 1 1987 he 
had just closed a big real estate deal and phoned his wife 
priscilla 33 to see if she could get a baby sitter so they could 
go out to dinner and celebrate 
when no one answered the phone andy drove the mile to his 
familys rustic house set on an isolated knoll in the woods he 
saw priscillas car in the driveway but the house was eerily dark 
he found his wife who was several months pregnant dead in 
their bedroom she had been sexually assaulted and shot twice in 
the head 
he doesnt remember everything that happened after that the 
trauma was such that he couldnt sleep through the night for six 
months 
he remembers going into the kitchen to call the police and his 
parents too afraid to look for his children because he feared he 
would find them dead 
when the police arrived andy sat in one of their cruisers an 
officer came out and told him his daughter abigail 7 and son 
william 5 had been drowned 
you lose total track of time he said the shock gives you 
the adrenaline to get through it at first but then it wears off 
after the murders andy stayed with his parents then rented an 
apartment in townsend but within a few months he moved back to his 
familys home 
i had to emotionally reclaim it he said i had to go back 
in there and be all right the house became a source of strength 
for me with the memories of my family the love that occurred 
there was much stronger than the death there 
the first months were difficult despite dinner invitations from 
friends who made sure he would not be alone andy said he joined a 
support group for the survivors of homicide victims 
its a roller coaster with no highs just different depths 
he said its a struggle just to get through each day 
first you sob all the time then you set goals like you say 
today im going to go shopping you dont want to go out and 
deal with people but then you go ahead and feel better because you 
did it 
self pity was not his strong suit 
you always think why me but you realize soon enough why 
not me if you live with your eyes open you know life isnt 
fair 
he gravitated to carol who understood better than most in their 
circle of friends from church what it meant to lose someone 
from the start they both said theyve talked out their mutual 
grief andy in particular still has his bad days 
my heart grieves for him carol said about those times 
