<TEXT>
a quartercentury before the lower 
mississippi delta development commission started roaming that 
region to chart solutions for its misery a similar agency had a 
similar mission to ease similar misery 
in 1964 president lyndon b johnson announced a national war 
on poverty from a front porch in inez ky the next year 
congress set up the appalachian regional commission which 
incorporated many of the poverty programs to help appalachia catch 
up with the rest of the nation in jobs health services education 
and transportation 
today improvements have been made but many of the 205 million 
people in the 13 states of appalachia still live in wretchedness 
in homes little more than shanties with no sewer systems and no 
running water 
the creeks around keystone are so dirty and dotted with toilet 
paper that locals have dubbed the result the charmin trail 
richard mullins a 44yearold unemployed miner who receives 
744 a month in government benefits lives with his wife and three 
children under a patchwork roof that leaks into one bedroom when it 
rains the floors are full of holes and sinking the paint is 
peeling and rats run about the house at will 
were still trying to find something better because this house 
is really not worth the 50 we pay a month said mullins wife 
darlene 
the appalachian region encompasses all of west virginia and 
parts of virginia kentucky tennessee north carolina south 
carolina georgia alabama mississippi ohio new york 
pennsylvania and maryland 
monroe newman senior economist for the appalachian commission 
asserts that the region as a whole is vastly better off with 2 
million more jobs than it had 25 years ago mainly in the service 
industries and with improved health care education and highways 
but better off is relative according to the latest data 
available from the appalachian commission based on the 1980 
census 14 percent of the regions people live below the poverty 
level nationally 124 percent of the populace is below that level 
their personal income per capita in 1987 averaged 12453 
compared to 15484 nationally last years average unemployment 
rate ran 59 percent sixtenths higher than the national average 
the poverty has spawned a host of social problems including 
drugs gangs and teenage pregnancies among youth who have little 
to do in some areas for instance it is a 40mile round trip to a 
movie 
the hardest hit towns are in the coaldominated counties of west 
virginia virginia kentucky and southeastern ohio newman said 
more than 100000 jobs have been lost in the appalachian coal 
fields since 1978 in some counties in these states unemployment 
runs more than twice as high as the national average 
they aint enough jobs for nobody said clady johnson of 
trammel va if kids graduate here they got to leave to get a 
job 
she knows firsthand her son gregory 23 enlisted in the army 
when he couldnt find a job mrs johnson who is divorced lives 
on 386 a month in government benefits 
the commission on religion in appalachia says that in spite of 
the obvious effectiveness of antipoverty programs the war was not 
won poverty rates remain unacceptably high and the risk of 
poverty is much greater for some regions and population groups than 
others 
it is bleak said jim sessions executive coordinator of the 
commission a coalition of 17 religious denominations formed to 
fight poverty survival is the name of the game 
sessions said things did improve in the late 1960s and through 
the 1970s with the economy rebounding and the building of 
hospitals clinics community colleges and highways 
but in the recession of the early 1980s he said appalachia 
lost 2 manufacturing jobs for every single job gained in the prior 
decade he especially noted coal jobs lost in west virginia and 
virginia steel jobs in pennsylvania and textile jobs throughout 
the tennessee valley 
in terms of employment and income all the progress we made 
was wiped out in two years at the beginning of the reagan 
administration and weve not regained it yet and probably wont 
sessions said weve moved our industrial base to a service 
resort and recreation economy which at best pays minimum wage 
