<TEXT>
decades of racism economic failure and 
indifference have sapped the mississippi delta region of 
opportunity and hope for many of its 8 million residents this 
final report of a fiveday ap extra series children of the 
delta examines whether the deltas future is destined to be its 
past 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the majestic steel bridge tall as an 
office tower and wide as a freeway was supposed to tie the 
lessdeveloped west bank of the mississippi river to the east 
banks world of industrial plants jobs and development 
but no traffic crosses the 81 million structure on the west 
bank below trash is heaped in weedchoked fields and shanties sit 
on squat pillars of red brick near the rivers edge a concrete 
pier a hundred feet tall holds up nothing but the clouds 
the gramercywallace bridge you see never was completed it 
was in the works for nine years but louisiana ran out of money and 
construction was halted in 1987 before access ramps were built 
so it goes in the mississippi delta today the unreachable span 
is a bleak symbol of just how difficult it is to bridge the gap 
between poverty and prosperity 
all we can do is hope and pray that they will finish the 
bridge and things will come better said jessie allen owner of 
allens bridgeview grocery store 
until the bridge is completed probably not until 1994 rusting 
and sometimes unreliable ferries fight the swift river current to 
move a handful of cars and a pittance of commerce across the river 
the nearest bridge is 30 miles upriver 
here as elsewhere up and down the impoverished delta region 
which includes parts of arkansas illinois kentucky louisiana 
mississippi missouri and tennessee the muddy river itself is at 
times a barrier blocking growth 
without good transportation plants have located elsewhere 
without jobs residents rely on food stamps and welfare without 
hope they move away or resign themselves to the heritage of 
poverty 
the mississippi river divides the region instead of unifying 
it said stan hyland a memphis state university anthropologist 
hyland has worked with the lower mississippi river delta 
development commission which has studied the region for 18 months 
its probably a quirk of history hyland said the unique 
history of the region the richness the river has worked against 
it its a great irony 
state and local leaders say reversing the deltas misfortunes 
will take improvement in education economic planning political 
relations among blacks and whites and building bridges and 
highways for development 
lake providence la has no bridge across the river its only 
claim to fame these days is that it has the highest unemployment 
rate about 18 percent in the state with the nations highest 
unemployment rate 
the river is a wall said ed dauphine president of the 
louisiana delta bank in lake providence across the river from 
mississippi 
we are a welfarebased economy and part of that is because i 
dont have any opportunity to sell any product in the state of 
mississippi theres not a nickels worth of commerce were dealing 
with over there 
the irony here as elsewhere in the delta is that the rich 
farmland may hold people back more than it helps them 
locals black and white say the few white families who own the 
land blocked development efforts for fear of raising the cost of 
farm labor high unemployment means an ample supply of cheap hoe 
hands seasonal laborers to chop cotton and tend fields 
its colonial said wilbur hawkins executive director of 
the delta commission the welfare system supports the poor and 
the rich and its going to take everyone working together to 
reverse that 
olly neal led boycotts of whiteowned businesses and established 
a health clinic for the poor in marianna ark in the early 70s 
today conditions are different neal said but not necessarily 
better 
i certainly dont believe that economically africanamericans 
are any better off he said we have no ownership in financial 
institutions for example and unemployment rates are comparable to 
the 70s 
now an attorney neal continues his fight but through the 
political process he was one in a group of blacks that 
successfully sued the state claiming arkansas legislative district 
boundary lines discriminated against blacks 
a federal judge ordered some lines redrawn and neal now 
believes the delta will have more than one black representative in 
the arkansas statehouse 
politics is the only place i think substantial change can come 
here in the delta and that change only comes by africanamericans 
being more insistent he said we have to insist on having an 
adequate share of the political offices 
change though doesnt come easy 
its much too slow for me neal said half the population 
here in the deep delta is africanamerican and almost none of 
the leadership that cuts out half of the ideas half of the 
enthusiasm 
half the population here is a drag on the other half half the 
team is sitting down not by choice but by acquiescence in part 
and by insistence of the white population 
most agree that improvement in the delta will be slow 
the problems of the region didnt get like this overnight and 
we cant fix them overnight either hawkins said we didnt 
plan to fail we failed to plan 
in a report to congress on may 14 the commission will recommend 
developing tourism as a means of economic growth along with 
regional cooperation on marketing delta products it will seek 
greater federal funds to help the poor and programs to help with 
education reform 
education is the key we know it said louisiana gov buddy 
roemer there are 8 million people in the delta and one 
characteristic stands out too many of us are not equipped 
educationally 
annie brown daughter of a sharecropper is already trying to 
make a difference 
in a palegreen classroom that was a sheriffs office six 
adults sing the alphabet to a rap beat before too long youll be 
picking up speed before you know it youll be able to read 
these students some unable to write their names when they 
enrolled are part of a volunteer literacy program in rolling fork 
miss run by mrs brown the program has attracted 242 residents 
in five years and 27 have passed highschool diploma equivalency 
tests 
her effort is being copied in other parts of the delta and 
commission members cite it as an example of the change that must 
come to improve the future 
im saying to the community lets educate our parents 
mother cannot read father cannot read so theres no reinforcement 
for the children mrs brown said in the black community nine 
out of 10 times if you find illiteracy the whole family is 
illiterate 
with little funding and only volunteers to help hers is a 
lonely battle one that typifies how difficult it will be to bring 
about change 
were trying to break the cycle mrs brown said the 
cycle must be opened up 
</TEXT>
