<DOCNO> AP900501-0192 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the french thought the next war would be as static 
as the last and built the maginot line to be an impregnable 
defense so the germans changed the rules and bypassed it with 
tanks and planes 
a generation of officers on both sides learned in world war i 
that unprotected infantry had little chance against artillery 
barrages and machinegun fire 
the french decided they needed fortifications against which 
german divisions would hurl themselves until they weakened and 
could be driven back the germans decided to go around and over 
fortifications with new forms of attack paratroops dive bombers 
and above all the battle tank 
frances line was named for andre maginot defense minister in 
192932 and stretched along 200 miles of the border with germany 
it included artillery protected by concrete 10 feet thick 
railroad tracks sunk into concrete formed barriers to stop tanks 
until gunners could blow them to pieces 
many fortifications were underground connected by a 
subterranean railway tens of thousands of soldiers could live in 
the vast bunkers 
we are always the invaded we are always the ones who suffer 
we are always the ones to be sacrificed said maginot who was 
wounded in world war i he died after eating bad oysters at a new 
years banquet in 1932 
his fortifications were strong but not long enough 
an agreement made before world war i committed france to defend 
belgium if it was attacked french politicians felt extending the 
line to the english channel would imply their generals preferred 
hiding in bunkers to defending belgian territory 
that left a doorway 200 miles wide including some of the most 
tankfriendly country in europe if hitler chose to violate belgian 
neutrality 
when france and britain declared war on germany after it invaded 
poland most of frances army waited in the maginot bunkers for a 
german attack that never came 
nine months of phony war eroded morale and readiness a 
politician who visited the maginot line wrote of being greeted by a 
senior officer wearing bedroom slippers 
french headquarters fell into despair after belgium and the 
netherlands collapsed the subsequent evacuation from dunkirk left 
the coastal plains of northern france wide open 
field marshal heinz guderians panzers breached the somme in 
force june 5 within a week 49 german divisions had crushed 
virtually all defenses in northern and eastern france 
on june 13 the wehrmacht turned on the maginot line and 
captured it from the rear more than 500000 men were taken 
prisoner most without firing a shot at the enemy and france 
signed an armistice june 22 
some of the bunkers now are open to the public as relics of 
military history others are used as mushroom farms 
</TEXT>
