<TEXT>
admitted inside trader dennis levine whose 
arrest led to the fall of ivan boesky and other wall street 
figures said his values eroded in the dealcrazy 1980s when 
milliondollar profits seemed insignificant 
i will regret my mistakes forever the former investment 
banker said in a firstperson article in the may 21 issue of 
fortune magazine which was released tuesday 
no one led me down the garden path levine said for 
the hard work and creativity i brought to my investment banking 
career i was well rewarded when i broke the law i was punished 
the system works 
it was levines first public comment on the illegal dealings 
that ended with his 1986 arrest since he was released from federal 
prison last year levine repeatedly has refused interview requests 
levine has set up his own mergers and acquisitions advisory firm 
and has lectured on ethics at top business schools including 
columbia and new york universities and the university of 
pennsylvanias wharton school 
a fortune spokeswoman said levine was paid to write the article 
she declined to specify the amount but said it was a normal 
freelance fee 
in the article a repentant levine traces his rise from a 
middleclass queens ny neighborhood to a managing directors 
suite at drexel burnham lambert inc from which he helped major 
takeover deals 
levine was involved in some of the 1980s biggest deals 
including ronald perelmans takeover of revlon inc and carl 
icahns proxy fight against phillips petroleum co 
the daily exposure to such deals the pursuit of larger and 
larger transactions and the numbing effect of 60 to 100hour work 
weeks helped erode my values and distort my judgment levine said 
in this unbelieveable world of billions and billions of 
dollars the millions i made by trading on nonpublic information 
seemed almost insignificant he said 
in his illicit dealings levine parlayed 39750 much of it 
borrowed from family members into 115 million over seven years 
using illegal tips on upcoming deals he set up offshore bank 
accounts and left instructions on how his trades were to be handled 
to avoid detection 
levine had a network of sophisticated insiders with whom he 
would swap deal information levine said boesky the former stock 
speculator would call him at home well before 6 am to ferret 
out information before trading 
levine said he would have gotten 24 million for supplying 
boesky with information but never received a penny because he 
was arrested first levine served 15 months in a federal prison 
camp in pennsylvania 
using information supplied by levine federal investigators 
nailed boesky who paid 100 million in penalties and pleaded 
guilty to one felony to settle insider trading charges boesky was 
released from federal custody in april after serving two years of a 
threeyear term 
levine said his scheme began crumbling when several bank 
executives were detected mimicking his trades which were executed 
via a swiss bank in the bahamas 
with the government in hot pursuit levine said he drove around 
manhattan in his bmw frantically calling his family and lining up 
an attorney on the car phone his unsuspecting wife laurie was 
furious he said 
pleading guilty to four criminal charges before a federal judge 
was a humbling experience perhaps as difficult as watching his 
daughter learn to walk in a prison waiting room he said 
levine said he has formed adasar group an advisory firm he 
named after his children adam and sarah though barred for life 
from working for a securities firm levine is allowed to advise 
companies 
levine said his clients are smaller than they used to be 
but he said his reentry into the business world has been met with 
fairness and compassion 
the magazine hits newsstands monday 
</TEXT>
