<DOCNO> AP900501-0217 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the us industrial sector expanded slightly 
during april for the first time in a year led by sharp gains in 
new orders and exports the nations purchasing managers said in a 
survey released tuesday 
economists said last months data although stronger than 
expected hardly pointed to an economic rebound most of the 
surveyed manufacturers remained reluctant to add new jobs or expand 
their inventories they said 
in addition a government report released tuesday showed the 
recent rise in interest rates was depressing construction a major 
component of economic growth spending for residential 
nonresidential and government building fell 14 percent in march 
to a 13month low the commerce department said 
i still think were dealing with an economy that is kind of 
sputtering said robert a brusca chief financial economist for 
nikko securities co international it may not look like a 
recession but you have to draw the line well short of calling it 
vibrant 
the national association of purchasing management said its 
economic index rose to 502 percent in april from 488 percent the 
previous month a reading above 50 indicates the manufacturing 
economy generally is expanding below 50 that it is generally 
contracting 
the april reading followed 11 straight monthly declines and was 
the highest since last aprils 527 percent level the group said 
in a news release from its tempe ariz headquarters 
the index has averaged 481 percent for the first four months of 
1990 consistent with a 13 percent rise in the gross national 
product the group said 
robert j bretz chairman of the trade groups business survey 
committee and director of materials management at pitney bowes 
inc said the improvement reflected a significant gain in new 
orders particularly in exports 
the rebound should be sufficient to sustain solid production 
growth for several months and buoy the entire economy over the 
balance of the second quarter he said 
some economists werent as optimistic 
we think growth in the second quarter could be less than it 
was in the first said carol stone a senior economist for nomura 
securities inc businesses are still showing a cautious 
attitude 
stone said manufacturers have kept their inventories low and 
have been reluctant to permanantly fill jobs 
brusca said a significant portion of the growth reported in the 
april purchasing managers report came from the volatile automobile 
sector 
the report said new orders expanded for the third consecutive 
month during april the new orders index jumped to 555 percent 
from 504 percent in march 
new export orders were up for the 28th consecutive month as the 
seasonally unadjusted index rose to 605 percent from 595 percent 
the report said 74 percent of the groups members exported last 
month up from 71 percent in march and a three year high 
imports increased for the fourth consecutive month but at a 
slower pace than march seventysix percent of all members imported 
in april down from 78 percent the group said 
the production portion of the survey gained ground for the third 
consecutive month during april although growth was at a slower 
level than the previous month 53 percent vs 544 percent 
declining for the 14th consecutive month was the employment 
portion of the survey with the index falling to 451 percent from 
452 percent members continued to report they were hiring 
temporary workers and working overtime to handle increasing 
production activity rather than hiring new employees the group 
said 
inventories weakened for the 17th straight month that index was 
unchanged from march at 416 percent the secondlowest level 
since december 1986 
supplier deliveries were faster in april for the 12th 
consecutive month but 12 commodities were in short supply 
including bearings electric motors timber and some chemicals the 
group said 
meanwhile prices of goods rose after falling for 10 consecutive 
months about 17 commodities had higher prices up from 11 in 
march the group said 
the purchasing managers report is based on a monthly survey of 
purchasing executives at over 300 industrial companies most of the 
figures are adjusted for seasonal factors 
</TEXT>
