<TEXT>
bristol myerssquibb co shareholders on 
tuesday overwhelmingly defeated a proposal that would have banned 
the consumer products giant from peddling infant formula directly 
to the public 
but the measure received enough votes to remain on the agenda 
next year 
the infant formula resolution sponsored by 11 religious 
investors and supported by many pediatricians received 1656 
million votes or 49 percent of the total at the companys annual 
meeting in wilmington 
more than 3209 million votes were cast against with 3112 
million absentions the measure needed to gain at least 3 percent 
of the votes to remain on the ballot at the next annual meeting 
a substantial part of the threehour meeting was dominated by 
debate over the infantformula resolution which has aroused 
considerable interest as a contentious shareholder activist issue 
in the 1990 annual meeting season 
the measures supporters said bristol myerssquibb is misleading 
the public by suggesting that its infant formula marketed though 
gerber products co is as nutritious as breast milk 
they say it departs from the industry tradition of promoting 
formula only to physicians since last october television ads for 
the formula end with the phrase if it doesnt come from you 
shouldnt it come from gerber 
how can you persist in this commercially driven charade 
said dr frank a oski chairman of the department of pediatrics at 
johns hopkins school of medicine and a representative of the 
american academy of pediatrics 
he urged adoption of the resolution which would make bristol 
myerssquibb and gerber stop marketing the formula directly to 
mothers 
