<DOCNO> AP900501-0232 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the food and drug administration on tuesday 
approved irradiation of poultry to control salmonella and other 
bacteria that cause foodborne illnesses but the industry said it 
had no plans to use the procedure 
the fda said irradiation is safe and effective in eliminating 
most bacteria in chicken turkey and other fresh and frozen birds 
making poultry safe for longer periods under refrigeration 
poultry companies however said they do not plan to use the 
technology because of consumer opposition and because the 
consumer can achieve the same thing by cooking the chicken said 
stephen pretanik science director at the national broiler council 
which represents the commercial broiler chicken industry 
there does not appear to be wide consumer acceptance for any 
food irradiation he said 
although cooking chicken thoroughly kills illnesscausing 
bacteria a lot of the sickness coming from chicken is coming 
from crosscontamination when raw poultry comes in contact with 
other food said george pauli consumer safety officer at fda 
irradiation of food was first approved in 1963 when the fda 
allowed its use to control insects in wheat and wheat flour later 
the fda approved its use to control insects spoilage and parasites 
in other grains fruits vegetables spices and pork 
irradiation of poultry is the first approved use aimed at 
controlling bacteria in food that cause illness in humans 
so far the process has been used infrequently because of 
consumer opposition food industry officials said when foods are 
irradiated they must be labeled that have been treated that way 
the fda on tuesday emphasized that the process does not make 
the food radioactive and as a result does not expose consumers to 
radiation 
but michael colby director of food and water inc a group that 
researches food safety and environmental issues said the fdas 
action was an outrage to consumers and to anyone who cares about 
safe food products 
he said scientific evidence that irradiation is safe is lacking 
and that by approving irradiation the fda is allowing poultry 
growers and processors to speed up their operations without having 
to clean up their facilities 
the problem with salmonella comes from the condition of 
poultry facilities and theyre filthy colby said the fda is 
proposing a toxic solution to a toxic problem 
colby also said the states of new york new jersey and maine 
prohibit the sale of irradiated foods 
in its approval the fda limited the amount of radiation that 
can be used on poultry to 3 kilogray doses of 1 to 10 kilogray are 
considered medium levels of radiation 
approval of irradiation for poultry was sought by the us 
department of agriculture which is responsible for inspecting meat 
and poultry products and radiation technology inc of rockaway 
nj a firm providing radiation treatment 
from 1973 to 1987 poultry accounted for 96 percent of the 
foodborne illnesses in outbreaks for which a food source was 
reported the fda said 
officials said there were no estimates on the incidence of 
foodborne illnesses in the united states but some estimate that 
nearly everyone gets sick from food every couple of years these 
illnesses range in severity from a stomach ache to death 
radiation could be used to control such bacteria as salmonella 
yersinia and campylobacter which are common in poultry and can 
cause gastrointestinal illnesses contamination can occur through 
other foods or when the poultry is not cooked thoroughly 
the fda said it based its approval on studies in which 
laboratory animals were fed diets containing irradiated poultry 
the study found the treatment to be effective and the treated foods 
to be safe 
</TEXT>
