<TEXT>
the us ambassador to japan asserted tuesday 
that japanese consumers will be among the main beneficiaries of 
easing barriers against american goods 
michael armacost also said progress has been made toward 
lowering japanese trade restrictions but the united states should 
continue to firmly press our requests on trade issues 
weve covered a fair amount of business in the past six or 
seven weeks armacost told a news conference its been 
satisfying to get some of these issues laid to rest 
armacost a career diplomat who was named ambassador a year ago 
was in seattle to speak to a japanamerica society meeting 
he said a developing consumerism movement in japan has resulted 
in more unhappiness at trade practices that keep prices of imported 
goods in japan artificially high 
theres a growing realization that these reforms are good for 
them he said 
lowering tariffs on wood products for instance raises the 
possibility that japanese could buy better housing armacost said 
there are enough benefits to be shared he said this should 
not be regarded as a oneway concession 
president bush last friday declined to cite japan under a 
section of us trade law that provides for economic retaliation if 
offensive trade barriers are not removed 
administration officials said targeting japan could provoke a 
public backlash against the united states and make it far more 
difficult for prime minister toshiki kaifu to reform japans 
trading system 
bushs decision was denounced by many members of congress who 
said the united states 49 billion trade imbalance with japan is 
bleeding american jobs and capital 
the bush administration last year cited japan under the 
socalled super 301 provision of the trade laws for barriers to 
usmade supercomputers satellites and wood products 
but in the past month us and japanese negotiators have 
reached agreements toward opening markets in all three of those 
areas 
the wood products agreement has been criticized by many 
northwest lawmakers and by small mill operators in the region as 
not going far enough but us trade representative carla hills 
said the agreement should boost us wood products sales by 1 
billion in 1991 
armacost said the agreements on computers satellites and wood 
products undoubtedly were hastened by a deadline for action set by 
the bush administration 
but he said the accords are a gesture of good faith from the 
japanese government that they are willing to resolve trade 
issues it would be inappropriate to impose super 301 now he 
said 
