<TEXT>
thousands of germans demanded protection 
against unemployment tuesday and labor leaders warned that western 
businesses are eager to exploit east germanys lowpaid work force 
in the west german capital bonn negotiators from both germanys 
met in an effort to complete by friday a plan for merging the 
economies and social institutions of the two nations 
an estimated 600000 workers held 700 rallies in both nations 
during may day gatherings tuesday 
in west berlin bands of mostly leftist radicals hurled 
firebombs and rocks tuesday night and police responded with tear 
gas and nightsticks more than 50 people were arrested after 
darkness fell in the tense kreuzberg district of the city west 
berlin police reported there were no immediate reports of injuries 
in the east german city of leipzig a group of leftist youths 
brawled with a band of neonazi youths in the market square the 
government news agency adn reported 
three suffered minor injuries and 21 were arrested the agency 
said 
authorities have feared that the newly opened borders between 
east and west germany would result in clashes that wold spread into 
east berlin as of late tuesday there were no reports of violence 
in east berlin 
in an earlier west berlin rally attended by 60000 bannerwaving 
east and west germans speakers voiced the fears that unification 
could bring high unemployment and an erosion of workers rights 
ernst breit head of west germanys federation of trade unions 
said some west german businesses and politicians view east germany 
as a new lowwage land with possibly less social security fewer 
controls and weak unions 
one east german listener 19yearold maria hoensch asked 
what sort of future will i have nobody knows what will happen 
economists have predicted that 500000 to 2 million east germans 
could lose their jobs in the next two years as inefficient 
stateowned enterprises are closed and others are forced to compete 
with western businesses 
government officials in both germanys say the effects will be 
temporary as western businesses flood into the east creating jobs 
and raising living standards 
the two germanys expect to complete agreement this week on the 
terms of an economic and social union that will go into effect on 
july 2 
differences remain between the governments on how much financial 
protection west germany will give east germans during the 
unification process 
officials from both countries met again in bonn to discuss the 
issues and planned to hold more meetings thursday and friday in 
east berlin 
both sides say they hope to have a final plan finished by friday 
for absorbing east germanys economy public sector and social 
welfare system 
the negotiators want the plan ready before east germans vote in 
their first free local and state election sunday voters had their 
first democratic national elections on march 18 
west germans fear higher taxes inflation and competition for 
jobs may be the cost of bailing out east germanys decimated 
economy 
west german chancellor helmut kohl who faces reelection in 
december denied that taxes would be raised and dismissed fears 
that inflation would result from replacing the nearly worthless 
east german mark for the powerful west german currency 
in an article to be published wednesday in the west german 
newspaper die welt kohl said the west german mark will remain 
the most stable and desirable currency in the world 
east german prime minister lothar de maiziere wants some job 
housing and social subsidies retained at least temporarily to help 
ease his nations transition from four decades of heavily 
subsidized socialism 
west german officials have agreed to exchange most east german 
marks at a 11 rate for west german marks when the western currency 
is circulated in the country in july 
the west german proposal calls for a 21 exchange for personal 
savings of more than 2300 but east germany is demanding a higher 
ceiling 
